    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain how lactic acid actually works in your muscles during high intensity training? like why does it make them burn and how does the body get rid of it after the workout is over?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During intense exercise, your muscles burn glucose faster than oxygen can be supplied, leading to anaerobic respiration which produces lactic acid. This buildup of hydrogen ions associated with lactic acid is believed to contribute to the burning sensation you feel. After exercise, the body efficiently clears lactate through the Cori cycle (converting it to glucose in the liver) and uses it as fuel by other tissues. Essentially, it's a metabolic byproduct that your body quickly processes and removes for energy or recycling.",
      "source": "target",
